    "HTF Level",
    "htf pd array",
    "HTF PD Array",
    "高时间框架水平"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A chart time frame above the working or entry time frame (e.g., daily when trading 15M) used to establish directional bias, identify key levels (PD arrays, swing highs/lows, fair value gaps, order blocks, session highs/lows), and provide context for lower time frame execution. Price must reach an HTF level before considering a trade.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Move up at least one time frame above the entry time frame (e.g., from 5-minute to hourly, hourly to daily) to establish the higher time frame context.",
    "Mark HTF key levels including PD arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps, volume imbalances), swing highs/lows with clear separation, session/period highs/lows (previous day, week, month), and levels from candle formations (open, equilibrium, T-Spot, wick midpoints following sweeps).",
    "Identify relevant HTF levels using a three-candle look-back window, focusing on candle closures that sweep prior extremes and close back inside the range (candle 2/3 closures).",
    "Determine directional bias by assessing HTF swing structure (higher highs/higher lows for bullish, lower highs/lower lows for bearish) and confirm through candle closures and displacement moves that break and retest range boundaries.",
    "Drop to the lower time frame only after price reaches a marked HTF level, seeking entry signals (change in state of delivery, sweep, SMT divergence, market structure shift) that align with the HTF direction.",
    "Ensure any LTF pattern is forming directly into the HTF level; if not, treat it as noise or a retracement to a deeper HTF level.",
    "A level is confirmed as an HTF level when price on the working time frame reaches it and produces a Change in the State of Delivery (displacement + close beyond a series of same-direction candles).",
    "An HTF imbalance (fair value gap) is identified on the higher time frame when three consecutive candles show non-overlapping wicks, creating a visible gap in price delivery.",
    "If London session fails to reach any marked HTF level, classify the setup as a potential New York Reversal and wait for price to reach the HTF level during the New York session.",
    "In SMC, the higher time frame must be at least twice the interval of the lower time frame; typically 30-minute, 1-hour, 2-hour, or 4-hour, with 1H, 2H, 4H providing the most reliable signals.",
    "Analyze market structure on the higher time frame to determine trend direction via break of structure, change of character, and reversal patterns.",
    "Identify and mark unmitigated order blocks (supply/demand zones) and fair value gaps as potential trading zones or points of interest for reversals.",
    "Wait for a clear engulfing candle on the higher timeframe that breaks out of the zone and engulfs prior reaction candles before entering a trade."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "HTF analysis establishes directional bias and key reaction levels that filter lower time frame trades. LTF setups are only valid when they form directly into HTF levels; otherwise, they are noise or retracements. The top-down workflow requires identifying the HTF context first, then dropping to the LTF for entry confirmation once price reaches the HTF level. Aligning LTF entries with HTF bias improves probability, and targets are governed by HTF structure. Avoid counter-HTF trades and chasing entries after HTF objectives are already met. In SMC, trades are taken only in the HTF direction, targeting important HTF levels, and candlestick confirmation (e.g., engulfing breakout) is waited for to improve reliability.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering on the lower time frame without first stepping up to the higher time frame to confirm key levels and directional bias.",
    "Taking trades at random price levels or LTF patterns that are not occurring directly into a marked HTF PD array, swing, or session level.",
    "Treating LTF market structure shifts, SMT divergences, or other signals as standalone entries without HTF directional alignment.",
    "Rushing into an entry when price first touches an HTF level without waiting for LTF confirmation such as displacement, sweep, or structural alignment.",
    "Trading counter to the confirmed HTF trend, expecting retracements to turn into reversals without HTF structural evidence.",
    "Continuing to enter after HTF key levels and targets have been reached, ignoring exhaustion of the move.",
    "Using the wrong candle components to define HTF range boundaries (e.g., wicks on 4h, bodies on daily) instead of the convention for that time frame.",
    "Classifying swing highs/lows as relevant without proper separation or using levels beyond the three-candle look-back window.",
    "Expecting perfect reactions at HTF wick midpoints without considering the overall HTF structure or seeking additional LTF confirmation.",
    "Applying session kill zone filters that do not align with the HTF being analyzed, leading to missed valid setups.",
    "Classifying a setup as a London Reversal when London forms a swing but never actually reaches a relevant HTF level — the correct classification is a New York Reversal.",
    "Acting on a Change in the State of Delivery before price has reached the HTF key level, resulting in premature entries that fail and continue in the original direction.",
    "Ignoring HTF imbalances (fair value gaps visible on higher time frames) as valid HTF objectives, and therefore missing the confirmation that price has reached its HTF target.",
    "Trading when the market direction on the higher time frame is unclear, which increases risk.",
    "Using a higher time frame that is not at least twice the lower time frame, leading to unreliable trend analysis.",
    "Applying the candle breakout strategy on lower time frames (e.g., 5-minute) leads to noisy signals and false engulfing patterns.",
    "Entering a trade at a higher time frame zone that has already been mitigated, rather than an unmitigated order block.",
    "Prematurely entering before the engulfing candle fully closes and engulfs the reaction candles' bodies and wicks."
  ],
